    <h1>Pro-Veiling Sources</h1>
    <hr>
    <h4>Evidence 1</h4>
    <ul>
      <li> The First Epistle to the Corinthians, authored by Paul, is addressed
        to:
        <blockquote>"Paul, a called apostle of Jesus Christ, through the will of
          God, and Sosthenes the brother, to the Assembly of God that is in
          Corinth, sanctified in Christ Jesus, called saints, <u><b>with all
              those calling on the Name of our Lord Jesus Christ in every
              place—both theirs and ours:</b></u> Grace to you and peace from
          God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ" <strong>- 1 Corinthians
            1:1–3 LSV<br>
          </strong></blockquote>
        <ul>
          <li>Paul is addressing the universal Church, not just the local church
            in Corinth.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> 1 Corinthians 1:16 concludes Paul's instructions on Christian head
        coverings:
        <blockquote> "But if anyone wants to argue about this, I simply say that
          we have no other custom than this, and neither do God's other
          churches." </blockquote>
      </li>
      <li> Biblical language scholar <a href="https://www.bible-researcher.com/biog.html">Michael
          Marlowe</a> cites 1 Corinthians 14:37:
        <blockquote> "If anyone thinks they are a prophet or otherwise gifted by
          the Spirit, let them acknowledge that what I am writing to you is the
          Lord’s command." </blockquote>
        <ul>
          <li> This demonstrates that Paul taught these traditions, including
            head covering, as commandments of the Lord. </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Evidence 2</h4>
    <p> <a href="https://www.benw3.com/">Ben Witherington III </a>(1995)
      explains: </p>
    <blockquote> "Paul is not simply endorsing standard Roman or even
      Greco-Roman customs in Corinth. Paul was about the business of reforming
      his converts' social assumptions and conventions in the context of the
      Christian community. They were to model new Christian customs, common in
      the assemblies of God but uncommon in the culture, thus staking out their
      own sense of a unique identity." </blockquote>
    <p></p>
    <p> <cite> Source: Witherington III, Ben (1995). <i>Conflict and Community
          in Corinth: A Socio-Rhetorical Commentary on 1 and 2 Corinthians</i>.
        Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing. pp. 235–38. ISBN 978-0-8028-0144-9. </cite>
    </p>
    <h4>Evidence 3</h4>
    <p> <a href="https://www.cbeinternational.org/person/philip-b-payne/">Payne,
        Philip Barton </a>(2015) argues: </p>
    <blockquote> "If Paul in 1 Corinthians 11:5 were requiring a garment
      covering the head, he would have been advocating something that was not
      customary for Greek women, nor was it customary in the Pauline or Petrine
      churches. Furthermore, Greek women, including women in prayer, were
      usually depicted without a garment covering the head. It does not make
      sense that Paul would assert something was disgraceful that in their
      culture was not considered disgraceful." </blockquote>
    <cite> Source: Payne, Philip Barton (2015). <i>Man and Woman, One in Christ</i>.
      Zondervan Academic. pp. 52–53. </cite>
    <p></p>
    <h4>Evidence 4</h4>
    <p> <a href="https://www.thegospelcoalition.org/blogs/justin-taylor/r-c-sproul-1939-2017/">R.C.
        Sproul </a>highlights: </p>
    <blockquote> "The practice of head covering is a uniquely Christian command,
      especially because the reasons for the command are uniquely Christian.
      Rather than Paul appealing to First Century culture, God's direction for
      the use of head coverings was actually counter-cultural." </blockquote>
    <cite> Source: Sproul, R.C. <i>Knowing Scripture</i>. InterVarsity Press,
      1977, p. 110. </cite>
    <p></p>
    <h4>Evidence 5</h4>
    <blockquote>
      <p>All the Early Church Communities agreed on veiling.</p>
    </blockquote>
    <p> <cite><a href="https://davidbercot.com/">Bercot, David W.</a> (1992). <i>Common
          Sense: A New Approach to Understanding Scripture</i>. Scroll
        Publishing Co., p. 66. ISBN 978-0-924722-06-6.</cite> </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>"Let all the women have their heads covered with an opaque cloth, not
        with a veil of thin linen, for this is not a true covering." –
        Hippolytus</p>
    </blockquote>
    <p> <cite>Source: Hippolytus, <i>The Apostolic Tradition</i>. Macmillan,
        1934, p. 43.</cite> </p>
    <p> <em><a href="https://www.logoslibrary.org/clement/instructor/311.html"><span><br>
          </span></a></em></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p> Irenaeus (c. 130 – c. 202), the last living connection to the Apostles
        who penned <i>Against Heresies</i>, explained that the "power" or
        "authority" on a woman's head when praying and prophesying was a cloth
        veil (<i>κάλυμμα</i> kalumma). </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p> <cite>Irenaeus, <i>Against Heresies</i>, Book 1, 8:2, cited in <i>The
          Ante-Nicene Fathers</i>, A. Cleveland Cox, ed. (1885), Vol. 1, p. 327.</cite>
    </p>
    <p> <cite>Tertullian (c. 155–220) emphasized the importance of substantial
        coverings for modesty and proper decorum in worship.</cite> <a href="https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0403.htm">On
        the Veiling of Virgins, Chapter 9</a> (c. 200 AD): </p>
    <div class="quote-container">
      <blockquote class="quote-design">
        <p style="text-align: left;"> "Is the reason she is allowed to go
          without a veil so that she can stand out and be noticed as she enters
          the church? Is it so she can show off her holiness by leaving her head
          uncovered? If she deserves recognition, wouldn’t it be better to honor
          her with some kind of leadership role or responsibility, rather than
          letting her disregard the practice of covering her head?" </p>
      </blockquote>
    </div>
    <div style="flex: 1;">
      <p style="font-size: 14px; color: #333333; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: left;">
        <b>Hippolytus of Rome</b> (c. 170–235), a prominent bishop and
        theologian, documented early Christian practices in his work <a href="https://www.stjohnsarlingtonva.org/Customer-Content/saintjohnsarlington/CMS/files/EFM/Apostolic_Tradition_by_Hippolytus.pdf">Apostolic
          Tradition, Chapter 18 (verse 5)</a> (c. 215). He wrote: </p>
      <div class="quote-container">
        <blockquote class="quote-design">
          <p style="text-align: left;"> "All women should cover their heads with
            a proper veil, not just a piece of thin linen, as that doesn’t count
            as a true covering." </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4></h4>
    <p style="text-align: justify;"><br>
    </p>
    <p style="text-align: justify;">These writers came from diverse backgrounds,
      ranging from the Greek-speaking East to the Latin West, and included
      theologians, bishops, and monastic leaders. Despite their differences,
      they all agreed that head coverings were a way to show modesty, humility,
      and respect for apostolic teachings.</p>
    <h4></h4>
    <h4>Evidence 6</h4>
    <p></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p> "Many Christian women also covered their hair, as enjoined by Saint
        Paul (1 Cor. 11:5) and as suggested by numerous medieval
        representations." </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p> <cite> <a href="https://pims.ca/people/linda-safran/">Safran, Linda</a>
        (2014). <i>The Medieval Salento: Art and Identity in Southern Italy</i>.
        University of Pennsylvania Press. p. 112. ISBN 9780812245547. <br>
      </cite></p>
    <h4>Evidence 7</h4>
    <blockquote>
      <p><span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book cs1">Given
            these considerations, it may be best to understand “authority on her
            head” in verse 10 as referring to the authority of the man (or
            husband). This authority allows the woman to pray and prophesy in
            worship as long as it is evident that she is under the authority of
            man, symbolized by the head-covering. The use of exousia in this
            context, where one might otherwise expect a direct reference to the
            head-covering itself, underscores its symbolic role.This
            interpretation is further supported by the chiasmic structure of
            verses 7–10, which clarifies Paul’s argument. Verse 7 states that
            man is the image and glory of God, while woman is the glory of man.
            Verses 8 and 9 emphasize the creation order, with woman created from
            and for man. Finally, verse 10 concludes that a woman ought to have
            authority on her head because of the angels, tying together the
            theological and practical implications of head-coverings in
            worship.In conclusion, while alternative interpretations suggest
            that “authority on her head” refers to a woman’s active authority,
            the traditional understanding—that the head-covering symbolizes her
            submission to the authority of her husband—remains more consistent
            with the cultural and theological context of Paul’s teaching. This
            view aligns with the broader scriptural narrative and the early
            Church’s understanding of this passage.</cite></span> </p>
    </blockquote>
