        <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
          <h4>Evidence 9</h4>
          <p>Ezra Palmer Gould, a professor at the Episcopal Divinity School,
            observed that both long hair and the veil served as coverings for a
            woman’s head. He explained:</p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>"The long hair and the veil were both meant to cover the head,
              symbolizing true womanhood and the proper relationship of woman to
              man. Thus, the absence of one carried the same meaning as the
              absence of the other."</p>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
        <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
          <div class="rt-hoverArea">
            <div class="rt-scroll">
              <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
                <div class="rt-hoverArea">
                  <div class="rt-scroll">
                    <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"> <span class="reference-text"><cite
                          id="CITEREFGould1887" class="citation book cs1"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ezra_Palmer_Gould">Gould,
                            Ezra Palmer (1887)</a>. <i>Commentary on the
                            Epistles To the Corinthians</i>. American Baptist
                          Publication Society. p.&nbsp;94.</cite></span></div>
                    <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"><br>
                    </div>
                    <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
                      <h4>Evidence 10</h4>
                    </div>
                    <blockquote>
                      <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"><span style="color: black;">According
                          to the Wycliffe Bible, early church history indicates
                          that the practice of wearing head coverings became
                          standard in major Christian centers such as Rome,
                          Antioch, and Africa. This custom was widely embraced
                          and established as a norm within the Church.</span></div>
                    </blockquote>
                    <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"><span style="color: black;"><br>
                      </span></div>
                    <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
                      <div class="rt-hoverArea">
                        <div class="rt-scroll">
                          <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"> <span class="reference-text"><cite
                                id="CITEREFJohnson1962" class="citation book cs1">Johnson,
                                Lewis (1962). <i>The Wycliffe Bible Commentary</i>.
                                Chicago: Moody Press. pp.&nbsp;<span class="nowrap">1247–</span>1248.</cite></span></div>
                          <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"><br>
                          </div>
                          <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
                            <h4>Evidence 1<span style="color: #222222;">1</span></h4>
                            <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book cs1"></cite><span
                                title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Wycliffe+Bible+Commentary&amp;rft.place=Chicago&amp;rft.pages=%3Cspan+class%3D%22nowrap%22%3E1247-%3C%2Fspan%3E1248&amp;rft.pub=Moody+Press&amp;rft.date=1962&amp;rft.aulast=Johnson&amp;rft.aufirst=Lewis&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHead+covering+for+Christian+women"
                                class="Z3988"></span></span></div>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      <blockquote>
                        <p>"Nature itself is therefore a divine confirmation of
                          the constitutional sense of the impropriety of women
                          appearing in the assembly without a head covering (v.
                          13). The words 'for her long hair is given to her as a
                          covering' (v. 15) do not mean that the woman's hair is
                          her covering and that she needs no veil—a view that
                          vitiates the force of 11:2–14. For example, if hair
                          were the only covering referred to in this passage
                          (11:1–16), then verse 6 would have to be translated,
                          'If a woman does not wear her hair, she should have to
                          have her hair cut or shaved off; she should wear her
                          hair,' which is quite ludicrous. Two coverings are
                          spoken of in the passage. This is established by the
                          fact that two different Greek words are used..."</p>
                      </blockquote>
                      <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book cs1"></cite><span
                          title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Commentary+on+the+Epistles+To+the+Corinthians&amp;rft.pages=94&amp;rft.pub=American+Baptist+Publication+Society&amp;rft.date=1887&amp;rft.aulast=Gould&amp;rft.aufirst=Ezra+Palmer&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHead+covering+for+Christian+women"
                          class="Z3988"></span></span> </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="https://books.google.ca/books/about/The_Local_Church_Today_and_Tomorrow.html?id=uq9TDwAAQBAJ&amp;source=kp_book_description&amp;redir_esc=y">Lee,
            Allan R. (2018). <em>The Local Church Today and Tomorrow: A Back to
              the Future Handbook on New Testament Principles</em>.</a> WestBow
          Press. ISBN 978-1-9736-1615-3.</div>
        <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output"><br>
        </div>
        <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
          <h4>Evidence 1<span style="color: #222222;">2</span></h4>
        </div>
        <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
          <blockquote>
            <p>On the whole, modern interpreters largely agreed that the
              covering Paul required was a veil or material headdress until the
              mid-twentieth century. Although the view that the covering
              referred to long hair had been popular among various groups
              throughout the 20th century, Abel Isaakson was the first to
              present an extended scholarly argument for this position in print.
              His work, <em>Marriage and Ministry in the New Temple</em>
              (1965), offered five key arguments:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>Contemporary Judaism had no prohibition against men covering
                  their heads during worship; in fact, priests were required to
                  wear headgear (e.g., Exodus 28:36–40; Ezekiel 44:18).</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>The Greek phrase ἀκατακαλύπτῳ τῇ κεφαλῇ corresponds to the
                  Hebrew phrase for "loose hair hanging down," as seen in the
                  Septuagint (e.g., Leviticus 13:45; Numbers 5:18).</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>The context of the passage focuses on hair, suggesting that
                  the implied object of ἔχων is τὴν κόμην ("long hair").</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>Verse 14 specifically identifies long hair as degrading for
                  men.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>Paul’s use of the term κεφαλή ("head") ties the discussion of
                  hair to his broader theological argument.</p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            <p>More recently, a growing number of scholars have independently
              reached similar conclusions. In a recent article, <strong>Francis
                Watson</strong> notes that this interpretation is gaining "broad
              consensus in recent scholarship." This view can be further divided
              into two camps:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>Those who see Paul’s concern as primarily about <strong>hair
                    style</strong> for both men and women.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>Those who focus on <strong>hair condition</strong>, arguing
                  that men must avoid long hair (as it is feminine) and women
                  must avoid loose hair, instead putting it up neatly.</p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>Despite this shift, the traditional interpretation—that Paul is
              referring to a <strong>material head-covering</strong>—continues
              to have contemporary supporters.</p>
          </blockquote>
          <br>
