              <div class="rt-content mw-parser-output">
                <h4>Evidence 1<span style="color: #222222;">2</span></h4>
                <blockquote>
                  <p>The practice of women wearing head coverings during public
                    worship is deeply rooted in the Word of God and supported by
                    Paul’s theological arguments. Individuals and churches must
                    prayerfully consider this issue and answer for themselves
                    before the Lord, without imposing it as a term of communion
                    with others.Paul’s exhortation in 1 Corinthians 11 addresses
                    the role of women in worship, emphasizing the theological
                    significance of head coverings. He grounds his argument in
                    creation, stating in verse 10, "For this cause (that is, the
                    woman being created for the man)..." This highlights the
                    divine order and the symbolic importance of head coverings
                    as a reflection of God’s authority structure.Recent
                    discussions have rediscovered the relevance of this
                    practice, noting that Paul’s use of theological arguments
                    makes it clear that godly women wearing head coverings in
                    public worship is a divine requirement. This practice
                    visibly reinforces God’s created order and serves as a
                    testament to the integrity of Scripture and Paul’s
                    teachings.In defending the head-covering issue, it is
                    essential to uphold:The integrity of God’s Word;The
                    integrity of Paul’s writings;A component of public worship
                    that visibly affirms God’s authority and created order.While
                    the practice may not be universally enforced as a term of
                    fellowship, its theological and symbolic significance
                    remains a vital part of biblical worship.</p>
                </blockquote>
                <p>Keddie, John W. (2019). The Church: Its Nature, Ordinances
                  and Offices. Lulu.com. pp. 225–238. ISBN 978-1-326-83069-4. </p>
                <p><br>
                </p>
                <h4>Evidence 1<span style="color: #222222;">3</span></h4>
                <blockquote>
                  <p>"The argument is often made that a woman’s hair is
                    sufficient as a covering, based on Paul’s statement in verse
                    15: <em>'her hair is given to her for a covering.'</em>
                    However, we must not assume that this single sentence
                    negates everything Paul has clearly established in the
                    preceding verses. The Greek word for 'covering' in verse 15
                    is peribolaion, which differs from katakalupto, the term
                    used earlier to describe the veiling. This distinction
                    indicates that while hair serves as a type of covering, the
                    veiling mentioned in the previous verses is intended to
                    fully cover the head and hair."</p>
                </blockquote>
                <p><br>
                </p>
                <p>Barnes, Allen; Barnes, Patti (1995). Christian Apparel. TEACH
                  Services. p. 50. ISBN 978-1-57258-029-9.</p>
