        <h4>Evidence<span style="color: #222222;"> 27</span></h4>
        <p><br>
        </p>
        <p>Paul's argument for veiling is rooted in the theological foundation
          of creation. Men should not wear a veil because they are the "image
          and glory of God," while women, as the "glory of man," are required to
          wear a veil as a sign of authority and respect for the divine order
          (Pages 231, 230). The necessity of veiling is signified by the word
          "ought" (opheilei), emphasizing its obligatory nature. Paul ties this
          practice to cultural norms, suggesting that married women typically
          wore veils in public, while unmarried women might not have been bound
          by the same custom (Page 225). The reference to "angels" in 11:10 adds
          a spiritual dimension, implying that the practice transcends cultural
          context and aligns with divine order.</p>
        <p>However, challenges to veiling arise from interpretations of specific
          phrases. For instance, the word "authority" in verse 10 has been
          linked to the wearing of a veil, though some suggest it reflects a
          broader sense of a woman's role and dignity. Additionally, the use of
          the preposition "anti" in 11:15 has been debated, with some arguing
          that it suggests a woman's long hair could suffice as a covering
          instead of a veil, potentially undermining the need for an additional
          covering (Pages 234, 237). This interpretation, however, is contested,
          as it contradicts earlier assertions in the passage that emphasize a
          physical covering (Page 237).</p>
        <p>Further, Paul clarifies that his argument does not imply the
          superiority of men over women. He seeks to avoid any misunderstanding
          that could arise from references to women being created from and for
          men. Instead, he emphasizes mutual dependence in the Lord, qualifying
          the hierarchical implications of his earlier statements (Page 235).</p>
        <p><br>
        </p>
