        <h4>Evidence<span style="color: #222222;"> 28</span></h4>
        <p><strong>Cultural and Archaeological Evidence</strong><br>
          The practice of veiling (e.g., veil, snood, cloak, or shawl) is
          supported by literary evidence and Greco-Roman statues, reliefs, and
          other archaeological artifacts, showing its widespread acceptance in
          historical contexts. (Page 189)<strong><br>
          </strong></p>
        <p><strong>Natural Symbolism</strong></p>
        <p>Leon Morris emphasizes that a woman's longer hair symbolizes the
          natural need for her head to be covered, aligning with nature's
          design. (Page 200)<strong><br>
          </strong></p>
        <p><strong>Historical Translation Consistency</strong><br>
          Early English translations, like the Revised Version (1881), reflected
          the interpretation that men should have "something on the head" and
          women should not be "bareheaded," supporting traditional covering
          practices. (Page 188)</p>
        <strong>Religious and Social Dishonor</strong>
        <p>Christian men who are covered dishonor themselves and Christ, their
          "head," while Christian women who do not coiffure or cover their hair
          bring shame, reinforcing the importance of veiling. (Page 184)<strong><br>
          </strong></p>
        <p><strong>Missionary and Cultural Context</strong><br>
          Paul ties veiling to the missionary witness to nonbelievers and the
          cultural expectations of a shame-honor society, suggesting its
          significance extends beyond personal piety to communal witness. (Page
          182)</p>
