        <br>
        The <strong>περιβόλαιον</strong> ("covering") is described as an <strong>analog</strong>
        of a woman’s long hair, meaning the two serve related but distinct
        purposes. The veil <strong>reflects or complements</strong> the natural
        beauty and modesty represented by long hair, rather than replacing it
        outright. This interpretation rebuts the "long hair thesis," which
        claims Paul argues that a woman's long hair <strong>replaces the need
          for an artificial covering</strong>. Instead, the passage asserts that
        Paul maintains the necessity of veiling as a <strong>symbol of
          propriety</strong>. Jerome Murphy-O’Connor suggested that περιβόλαιον
        refers to hair wrapped around the head, interpreting Paul’s statement as
        advocating only for long hair, without requiring a veil. This reading is
        explicitly criticized as a misinterpretation because: The Greek
        preposition ἀντί ("as") is interpreted here to indicate correlation or
        complementarity, not substitution. The passage rejects the idea that
        long hair alone fulfills the symbolic requirements Paul outlines.
        Instead, it emphasizes that: Men: Short hair and no veil. Women: Long
        hair and a veil, both serving distinct but interconnected purposes in
        reflecting gender roles and maintaining modesty. Martin controversially
        interprets περιβόλαιον as referring metaphorically to "testicles,"
        suggesting that Paul’s argument contrasts women’s long hair (as their
        natural "covering") with men’s testicles, viewed as their corresponding
        natural marker of masculinity. This theory relies on ancient
        physiological conceptions and is unconventional. The passage rejects
        this interpretation, emphasizing that περιβόλαιον simply means "a head
        covering." (p. 72).<br>
        <br>
        “ Not only is Corinth sur-rounded by other cities where veiling is
        documented, 30 but Pausanias indi-cates that in whole cloth fashion all
        the Greeks share common cultural29) Strabo (11.13.9-10) records the view
        of ‘some’ (τινές) who say that Medea introducedinto Greek culture the
        wearing of a veil even over the face (καὶ ἐπικρυπτομένην τὴνὄψιν).30)
        See n. 14.64 P.T. Massey / Novum Testamentum 53 (2011) 52-72customs-if
        these customs can be traced back to Homer.31 Th is, it must beadded,
        should not come as a surprise as Homer was the literary instrumentfor
        transmitting Greek culture from one generation to the next.” (pp.
        63-64).<br>
        <br>
        “Paul is not saying that long hair replaces a veil. On the
        contrary,veiling is a reflection or extension of long hair. A woman’s
        hair is to be in a natural state, not curled or braided. And it is to be
        covered with a veil.53 Th e veil thus follows the contour of a woman’s
        long hair and accentuates the glory (δόξα) of her natural beauty without
        creating the social stigma of either immodesty or ostentatiousness. The
        emphasis upon her dress is not<br>
        one of glamor but one of simplicity.” (p. 72).</div>
      <div class="rt-scroll"><br>
      </div>
      <div class="rt-scroll">The author cites several sources for linguistic and
