      <div class="rt-scroll">
        <h4>Evidence<span style="color: #222222;"> 41</span></h4>
        Wm. O. Walker, Jr. proposed an intriguing hypothesis to address the
        well-known challenges of interpreting <strong>1 Corinthians 11:2–16.</strong>
        He suggested three key points: (a) the entire section is an
        interpolation, (b) it is composed of three originally independent texts,
        and (c) none of these texts were authored by Paul. While this bold
        approach might initially appeal to those familiar with the complexities
        of this passage, a closer analysis reveals that the supporting arguments
        are highly problematic, both factually and methodologically.</div>
